combos.name: treatment_preferences
combos.snippet: The member indicates no preferences with regard to counselor gender, communication style, or treatment type.

combos.name: Member's care will consist of...
combos.snippet: Member's care will consist of Suboxone MAT coupled with weekly group therapy aimed at decreasing ambivalence about moving toward abstinence, increasing knowledge of evidence-based strategies for sobriety, building up coping skills that can stand in place of substance use for stress relief, increasing ability to problem-solve, and forging stronger and broader community supports for the individual. Member will focus on becoming abstinent, eventually tapering from Suboxone, and developing the coping skills needed to face life stressors without drugs.

combos.name: TopicCharacteristicsOfSafetyNets
combos.snippet: People who can be Safety Nets for me will have the following qualities: Not actively drinking or using; Good at listening; Knowledgeable about addiction (or willing to learn); Respectful toward me; Nonjudgmental; Trustworthy; Kind; Nurturing; Patient; Willing to make time for me; Genuine; Interested in sharing thoughts, perspectives, and ideas; Protective of me and my recovery.

combos.name: TopicEarlyWarningSignsOfRelapse
combos.snippet: The counselor led group on relapse prevention by detection of early warning signs, such as increased negative affect, increased interpersonal conflicts, and social pressures to engage in illicit use. Discussed charting out relapse roadmaps as part of the relapse prevention planning process, and also discussed the importance of being aware of the Abstinence Violation Effect and not allowing low self-efficacy to lead to ongoing use after a lapse.

combos.name: pot_education
combos.snippet: The counselor provided the member with information regarding marijuana's deleterious effects on health, mental functioning, and recovery efforts.

combos.name: TopicRedFlagThoughts
combos.snippet: An argument starts inside your head: your rational self versus your addiction. You feel as though you are in a fight, and you must come up with many reasons to stay sober. Your addiction is really just looking for an excuse, a relapse justification. The takeaway: allowing yourself to continue thinking about alcohol or other drug use is choosing to start a relapse. The farther the thoughts are allowed to go, the more likely you are to relapse.

combos.name: relapse_drift
combos.snippet: Discussed relapse drift, that phenomenon characterized by a member gradually easing up on those behaviors, thoughts, and surroundings they maintained that initially led to sobriety. Discussed that most members don't just suddenly relapse without warning. Instead, there are signs. Helped members identify behaviors and thoughts that likely signal they are drifting toward a relapse on their recovery journey.

combos.name: TopicMooringLines
combos.snippet: In becoming sober, you have had to learn to adopt certain new behaviors—behaviors that work for you to keep you sober. It is too easy to accidentally drop one or more of these mooring lines and allow your recovery to drift toward relapse. Charting the new behaviors and occasionally checking to make sure the lines are secure can be very useful. The counselor showed members how to chart mooring lines and avoided behaviors in support of sobriety.

combos.name: TopicWellness
combos.snippet: A healthy body. Good physical health habits. Nutrition, exercise and appropriate health care. These make up the physical dimension of wellness. A few ways we can get there might be choosing things that make our body feel good and trimming back the things that bring us down. We can also feel better by creating a routine that balances activity with inactivity - and that is manageable within our obligations and needs. Our body is intelligent and learning to listen to it more deeply may be very important and empowering. The Social Wellness Dimension involves having healthy relationships with friends, family and the community and having an interest in and concern for the needs of others and humankind.

combos.name: TopicStagesOfChange
combos.snippet: Reviewed with member’s the five stages of change and discussed that members may move forward and backward along this continuum before achieving long-term sobriety. Discussed ways to boost motivation for sustained change, and how to cope with ambivalence regarding the process of change.

combos.name: SelfHelp
combos.snippet: Expand members of the support network, increase member's education regarding substances and recovery, and provide accountability partners and recovery mentors.

combos.name: N/S
combos.snippet: Member N/S group today. Counselor telephoned, texted, and emailed to reengage member in treatment. Call went unanswered. Counselor left voicemail and text message for member to contact counselor and discuss reason for absence and possibility of a makeup group.

combos.name: grounding_
combos.snippet: The counselor led a group discussing the way in which negative thought and emotions can sometimes overwhelm us during our recovery journey, and the need to be able to manage these in a way that lets us focus on the present and to an extent detach from psychic pain. Presented grounding techniques, gave examples, and asked member how they therapeutically distract themselves when overwhelmed by negative cognitions or emotions.

combos.name: topic_healthyrelationships
combos.snippet: Healthy relationships are the exact opposite of what you are likely used to from your addiction days. In fact, unhealthy relationships are often at the root of our addictions. Addiction maintains a life of secrecy and fear. Such attitudes do not fare well with a relationship—hiding things and not being truthful with oneself or others are not conducive to healthy behaviors. But, you can have healthy relations in recovery! Healthy relationships are based on reality, not fantasy. If you build your relationship on the reality that you are both unique and have your own strengths and weaknesses, you will be working toward a healthy common ground. Keep recovery at the forefront of your mind. If you find yourself in a relationship with someone that does not respect your boundaries and is using drugs or alcohol around you—walk away.

combos.name: topic_posttraumaticgrowth
combos.snippet: Would you be surprised to learn that you, like most people, are more resilient than you may have realized? Keep in mind that it’s normal to grieve, cry or even behave foolishly; it’s also common and even healthy to feel anxious, angry, or depressed after traumatic events. These are a normal aftermath of experiencing trauma. Sometimes, a little extra effort is precisely what prepares us for the next obstacle to be faced. As you journey through recovery, keep in mind that struggling is an important part of any growth experience. Fortunately, when people know that trauma most likely leads to resilience, personal transformation and post-traumatic growth, they have better thoughts; such as, “This is hard, and I’m not comfortable, but I’ll eventually make it.” PTG (post-traumatic growth) does not happen overnight. Instead, it unfolds over a long period of time. PTG also appears paradoxical. In embracing your vulnerability, you grow stronger. Resilience can help maintain good and stable recovery, and if relapse does occur, resilience is also what prevents the relapse from spinning out of control. We can all learn how to turn traumas into growth opportunities.

combos.name: topic_resolvingambivalence
combos.snippet:
No matter how motivated you feel about your recovery and its importance in your life right now, it is very normal to feel ambivalence, or mixed feelings, about the process of changing your behavior and lifestyle (Prochaska, DiClemente, and Norcross 1992). 

Even though your use of alcohol or drugs has caused problems for you that have led you to think about changing, there was a reason that you started drinking or using in the first place. The reason was, it was doing something that felt good or helpful to you, whether it was making you feel positive emotions or enhancing your ability to function in some way, or removing unpleasant feelings. 

It is important to acknowledge that there were some positive rewards that you got out of drinking or using back when you started, and the hope to continue to get those benefits can lead you to have mixed feelings about giving it up, even if you have not experienced many positives from drinking or using for a while. Those memories are powerful, and your addicted brain will tempt you to seek out alcohol and drugs in attempts to repeat these positive experiences. 

As you examine your motivation for change, you will begin the process of strengthening the power of your rational brain to control your addictive behaviors.

combos.name: topic_totalabstinence
combos.snippet:
There are many reasons total abstinence is a necessary goal for recovering people. A few of them are the following: follow-up studies show that stimulant users are eight times more likely to relapse if they continue using alcohol and three times more likely to relapse if they use
marijuana. You can greatly reduce your chances of relapsing by maintaining total abstinence. Places and people associated with drinking are often the very places and people that are triggers for drug use. When you’re learning to handle problems without resorting to drug or alcohol use, using another drug or alcohol to numb the uncomfortable learning process 1. Blocks your chance to practice coping without running away. 2. Puts you at risk for becoming dependent on the alcohol or secondary drug.

combos.name: topic_guiltandshame
combos.snippet:
Guilt is feeling bad about what you have done. Shame is feeling bad about who you are. Feeling guilty is a healthy reaction. It often means you have done something that does not agree with your values and morals. It is not unusual for people to get into situations where they do things they feel guilty about. What is important is making peace with yourself. Sometimes that means making up for things you have said and done. Sometimes it means realizing you are feeling guilty unnecessarily. No one knows all the reasons that some people can stop using once they decide to and other people cannot. Research shows some of the reasons have to do with family
histories, genes, and individual physical differences in people. They do not have to do with some people being bad, stupid, or weak. Addiction affects people differently. What we do know is that you cannot recover by these means: 1. Trying to use willpower; 2. Trying to be strong; 3. Trying to be good
It takes two things to make recovery work: 1. Being smart; 2. Working hard

combos.name: Eval_Dec21
combos.snippet:
Accomplishments for 2021: (1) Promoted to Clinical Field Trainer and assisted in onboarding over 70 new clinical staff members this year, receiving 'exemplary performance' feedback per Breanna Kostraba's report; (2) assisted KY clinical staff in strengthening documentation skills while shepherding these staff through a difficult transition between outgoing and incoming clinical supervisors; (3) picked up three additional groups in November and December 2021 due to clinical staff attrition.

Needs fom Management: I can't say enough positive things about the support I have received at all levels of management in the past eighteen months. My clinical supervisor has been extremely supportive and collegiate, and I send kudos her way. 

Growth: I'd like to pick up some specialized training in Trauma Informed Care, sufficient to become a certified trainer; I'd like to then train and certify one or more other Trauma Informed specialists among our KY staff. I'm also interested in growing into an expanded role in Learning and Development if that role involves upward career mobility.  Goals: The three goals I'd like to reach to make my KY team more successful are (a) bringing greater awareness to clinical staff about the role trauma plays in the development and continuity of addiction; (b) working more closely with KY clinical supervisors to offer training opportunities to clinical staff; and (c) working with CS and leadership to help staff understand the nuances involved in implementing our policies and procedures in a member-centered fashion.

combos.name: balancing_shoulds_wants
combos.snippet:
Are the things you are spending your time doing things that you are obligated to do, or are they things that you find enjoyable? The key is to have a balance between the two. Often the scale is tipped in the direction of lots of should dos, or activities that are part of your responsibilities. This can feel very unfulfilling, and can lead to guilt, confusion, or dissatisfaction with life. On the other hand, when people are doing a lot of pleasurable activities and not working on any long-term goals, this can create a void, or a feeling of underachieving or not accomplishing enough. Lets take a look at your personal balance of responsibility and fun, so that you can decide where you
need to focus your efforts.

combos.name: _readmission
combos.snippet:
READMISSION
i. Members who have been discharged through a care team-driven discharge,
may present for intake to re-enter the program after 30 days, unless they have
been banned on the basis of prior behavior. They must be able to identify why
they were previously unsuccessful. If the barriers to successful treatment have
not been resolved, the member should not re-enter the program, regardless of
how much time has passed. Prior to this decision, there shall be a discussion
and agreement amongst the treatment team.
ii. Members who have been discharged due to financial reasons may be
reconsidered for intake sooner than 30 days after discharge, provided they are
compliant with all financial policies at the time of re-intake evaluation.
iii. Members who have been discharged via a member-driven discharge (i.e. “loss
of engagement”) may be re-admitted as soon as they represent and express a
desire to re-initiate treatment.
iv. Members who have been discharged via a “member-driven discharge” within the
last 30 days and present for readmission, may receive an abbreviated
readmission evaluation process by a counselor and provider to expedite
continuity of care.
v. Any delay or expedition in readmission after a care team driven discharge may
be waived by the Clinical Director at the request of the care team.
vi. The Counselor will make the determination about readmission collaboratively
with the provider.

combos.name: LGBTQIA+ groups
combos.snippet:
There is nothing in any professional code of ethics that prevents counselors from having their own personal values. Professional counselors represent a diverse group of all races, ethnicities, religions, and other socioeconomic backgrounds. However, the profession emphasizes the value of honoring and respecting the uniqueness and diversity of clients and specifically speaks against counselors acting in a discriminatory way.

In both codes of ethics, the need for cultural awareness and responsiveness in the context of the counseling relationship are incorporated into the ethical standards. Counselors must learn about cultures different than their own to increase their understanding of clients they may have from other cultures. You should make every effort to be aware of the ethnocultural background and worldview of each client and work within that framework to achieve goals in partnership with them.

Cultural humility is also important. Cultural humility is the practice of remaining teachable and open to the perspectives of those from cultures other than your own. At the same time, you must acknowledge that it is not possible for you to fully learn and understand all of it at any given point in time, it is an ongoing process. This is because culture is constantly evolving and cultural norms can be interpreted differently by each person (Lekas et al, 2020).

What should you do if your personal beliefs threaten to cloud your ethical decision making? You do not have to ignore your values. However, you must base your professional decisions on the values and principles outlined in ethical codes for counselors and be sure that they prevail when your values conflict with what is required of you.

To understand how ethical problems can emerge, you must be aware of how your values may conflict with those of your profession. This requires continual reflection on your part.

combos.name: quality_specialist
combos.snippet:
Responsibilities
At Groups, the quality specialist is an integral part of the quality and research team and helps
ensure that Groups is providing the highest quality of care to our members. Specifically, the
quality specialist leads our monthly chart review process, assists in the quality team’s
investigation of and response to critical events and incidents, and assists with any additional
quality projects, external reviews, and reporting needs, as instructed by the Director of Quality.
Duties & Responsibilities
 
Chart Reviews (70%)
Complete clinical quality chart reviews, helping to produce sufficient sample size of quality auditing to meet monthly quotas.
Pull, collect, and analyze chart review data submitted by other team members (clinical supervisors, medical directors, etc)
Identify trends and areas for improvement and opportunity
Collaborate with clinical and operational teams as needed
Critical Events and Incidents (15%)
Respond to critical incidents and events by completing important investigations of clinical quality (chart reviews, interviews, etc).
Facilitate critical event debrief meetings (i.e. multidisciplinary reviews)
Assist on any external audits related to critical events/incidents
Data Analysis and Reporting (10%)
Aggregate data and assemble monthly, quarterly, and annual quality reports
Additional Projects and Duties (5%)
Assist the quality team with any additional projects and external reviews
Performs other duties as assigned
